******
[5] Singapore
Date: Thu, 30 Jun 2005 17:15:39 -0400 (EDT)
From: Alfonso J Rodriguez, MD <ajrm_msds@yahoo.es>
Source: Channel News Asia.com. June 30, 2005 [edited]
<http://www.channelnewsasia.com/stories/singaporelocalnews/view/155531/1/.html>


Anti-dengue measures intensified as number of dengue cases go up in June
---------------------------------------------------
The number of dengue cases has gone up in June 2005 due to warmer weather.

On average, there were about 300 cases per week, more than double the
weekly average in the last 3 months. March, April and May saw a
weekly average of 136 cases.

To curb the rise, especially as the warm weather is expected to
continue, the National Environment Agency (NEA) has extended its
campaigns to MRT stations and trains.

About 900 posters have been up since the beginning of June to educate
commuters about the dangers of the Aedes mosquitoes. About 50 SMRT
trains will be carrying the message till the middle of August.

NEA has said that for the first 3 weeks of June, there were about 610
cases, compared to 611 for the whole of May. In 2004, the number of
cases in June was 617 cases, compared to 470 the previous month.

According to the NEA, the number of dengue cases from the start of
2005 to the 3rd week of June stands at nearly 5000, more than double
the same period of 2004.

The warmer weather in June, July and August traditionally brings
about a spike in the number of dengue cases. That's because the
female _Aedes_ mosquito, which carries the virus, breeds faster in
such weather, and the infective period is also shorter. To tackle
this, NEA has intensified its awareness and outreach efforts.

"On the train there are 2 million commuters commuting every day, so
the train is a very good medium for us to spread the dengue
prevention message," said Dalson Chung of the Environment Health
Department of the NEA.

On the ground, NEA has also increased its search and destroy efforts
to reduce the _Aedes_ mosquito population.

In the 1st 5 months of 2005, it carried out more than 170 000
inspections of premises for breeding grounds, including parks and
vacant lands. It is also working with town councils to flush out
breeding grounds on roof tops and pump rooms.

Mosquito breeding in homes also went up and more owners were fined,
from 68 in February 2005 when fines were introduced, to more than 230
in May.

From January up to 14 May, there were 3552 cases of dengue fever and
94 cases of dengue haemorrhagic fever. So far only one death has been
reported.

NEA said that although more households may be aware of dengue, it
hopes that this awareness will translate into action to curb mosquito
breeding grounds.

[Byline: Hasnita A Majid]

--
Alfonso Rodriguez, M.D.
